  "summary": "Miss Marple visits Letitia Blacklock to deliver a note from the vicar, but she is dismissed by Inspector Corrigan, who views her as a meddling busybody. While Corrigan privately believes Miss Marple could be in danger from an unidentified killer, he maintains a professional demeanor. He expresses guilt over the death of Miss Bonner and pressures Miss Blacklock to help solve the case, specifically regarding the identity of Sonia Goddard, a woman from thirty years prior.\n\nThe Inspector questions Miss Blacklock about Sonia’s appearance and asks if she suspects any current acquaintances, such as Mrs. Swetnam, Miss Inchcliff, or Miss Mulgrew, might be Sonia. Miss Blacklock finds the suggestion of Mrs. Swetnam absurd but agrees to search for old photographs. After locating Julia, who had been in the attic, the Inspector and Julia retrieve two old albums from a cabinet in the study. \n\nUpon examining the albums, the Inspector discovers that several photos have been removed, leaving blank spaces in the pages. Both Miss Blacklock and Julia note that these spaces were not present when they previously looked at the albums, leading the Inspector to conclude that someone recently removed all photographs of Sonia.\n\nIn a separate scene, an unnamed individual confronts Mrs. Hammers (also referred to as Mrs. Hames or Mrs. Hemmings) in her study. The individual challenges her previous claim that her husband was killed in Italy, suggesting instead that he was a deserter. Mrs. Hammers reacts with bitterness to the dredging up of her past.",
